C6: 
<taxonomicName id="4C6A4D06FFC3FFD5FF19FBABBDA7CB66" authority="Juel, Bot. Notis. 1892" authorityName="Juel, Bot. Notis." authorityYear="1892" box="[184,658,1094,1121]" class="Pucciniomycetes" family="Pucciniaceae" genus="Puccinia" kingdom="Fungi" order="Pucciniales" pageId="16" pageNumber="237" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="vaginatae">
<emphasis id="B91EEA97FFC3FFD5FF19FBABBEA0CB66" bold="true" box="[184,405,1094,1120]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="237">Puccinia vaginatae</emphasis>
Juel, Bot. Notis. 1892
</taxonomicName>
–1893: 56, 1893. (
<figureCitation id="13512A00FFC3FFD5FCFFFBABBC94CB66" box="[862,929,1094,1120]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="17.[136,229,1449,1471]" captionTargetBox="[203,1385,191,1424]" captionTargetId="figure-18@17.[203,1385,190,1425]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 9. Puccinia vaginatae on Saussurea sp. (A–F) and Carex sp. (G–I). A. Plants producing spermogonia and aecia on the leaf surface in the field. B. Vertical section of a spermogonium. C. Vertical section of an aecium surrounded with peridia. D. Aecia on the lower leaf surface. E. Aeciospores with granules on the surface observed under SEM. F. An aecium observed under SEM. G. Telia on the lower leaf surface. H, I. Vertical section of a telium. Scale bars: B = 20 μm, C = 30 μm, E = 5 μm, F, H, I = 50 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6416777" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6416777/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="237">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
)
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C370650EFFC3FFD5FF29FB63BFF4CAEA" pageId="16" pageNumber="237" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BD53685FFC3FFD5FF29FB63BD16CA3E" blockId="16.[136,1452,1166,2021]" pageId="16" pageNumber="237">
<emphasis id="B91EEA97FFC3FFD5FF29FB63BE0DCBAE" bold="true" box="[136,312,1166,1192]" pageId="16" pageNumber="237">Description:—</emphasis>
<emphasis id="B91EEA97FFC3FFD5FE99FB62BEF8CBAF" box="[312,461,1167,1193]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="237">Spermogonia</emphasis>
amphigenous, surrounded by greenish-yellow lesions, densely grouped, honey-yellow, subepidermal, flask-shaped, 
<typeStatus id="54D18827FFC3FFD5FE6FFB5EBECBCBCB" box="[462,510,1203,1229]" pageId="16" pageNumber="237">type</typeStatus>
4 of 
<bibRefCitation id="EFFB4B74FFC3FFD5FDE3FB5FBCA8CBCA" author="Cummins, G. B. &amp; Hiratsuka, Y." box="[578,925,1202,1228]" pageId="16" pageNumber="237" refId="ref19116" refString="Cummins, G. B. &amp; Hiratsuka, Y. (2003) Illustrated genera of rust fungi, 3 rd ed. American Phytopathological Society, St. Paul, Minnesota, USA." type="book" year="2003">Cummins &amp; Hiratsuka (2003)</bibRefCitation>
. 
<emphasis id="B91EEA97FFC3FFD5FC0AFB5EBCDECBCB" box="[939,1003,1203,1229]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="237">Aecia</emphasis>
is mostly hypophyllous, cupulate with peridia, 
<taxonomicName id="4C6A4D06FFC3FFD5FF45FB3BBE7BCBF6" box="[228,334,1238,1264]" class="Pucciniomycetes" genus="Aecidium" kingdom="Fungi" order="Pucciniales" pageId="16" pageNumber="237" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B91EEA97FFC3FFD5FF45FB3BBE7BCBF6" box="[228,334,1238,1264]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="237">Aecidium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
- 
<typeStatus id="54D18827FFC3FFD5FEF7FB3ABEBECBF7" box="[342,395,1239,1265]" pageId="16" pageNumber="237">type</typeStatus>
. Peridial cells firmly conjunct, cubic to polygonal, hyaline. 
<emphasis id="B91EEA97FFC3FFD5FB88FB3ABB84CBF7" box="[1065,1201,1239,1265]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="237">Aeciospores</emphasis>
catenulate, globose to subglobose, angular, 15.5–18.0 × 13.0–17.5 µm (av. 17.0 × 14.5 µm); walls hyaline, 0.4–0.8 µm (av. 0.6 µm) thick, densely verrucose with big granules.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BD53685FFC3FFD5FF1CFAAEBFF4CAEA" blockId="16.[136,1452,1166,2021]" pageId="16" pageNumber="237">
Immature 
<emphasis id="B91EEA97FFC3FFD5FE92FAAFBEA4CA5A" box="[307,401,1346,1372]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="237">uredinia</emphasis>
is rarely found. 
<emphasis id="B91EEA97FFC3FFD5FDF2FAAFBDBFCA5A" box="[595,650,1346,1372]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="237">Telia</emphasis>
hypophyllous, blackish brown, rounded to broadly elliptic, erumpent. 
<emphasis id="B91EEA97FFC3FFD5FF29FA8BBE32CA86" box="[136,263,1382,1408]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="237">Teliospores</emphasis>
broadly clavate, ellipsoid, truncate, rounded or conical at apices, middle or weakly constricted at the septa, rounded or attenuate at the bases, 36.0–53.0 × 15.0–19.5 µm (av. 43.5 × 17.5 µm); walls pale brown, 0.6–1.2 µm (av. 0.8 µm) thick at sides, 6.6–13.5 µm (av. 10.0 µm) at apices; pedicels persistent, hyaline, 14.0–30.0 µm (av. 22.0 µm) long.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
